The glassfish container depends on its version, seems to have overridden your default JDK Keystore file to its own path.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;If other java apps in this machine work fine, the only issue is glassfish can&#39;t work, try this&lt;/strong&gt;

    System.clearProperty(&quot;javax.net.ssl.trustStore&quot;); //add in servlet init()
This should run once when the servlet starts up, it will override glassfish Keystore with system default Keystore, which should work fine.

If your servlet doesn&#39;t have an init, add this into your startup servlet class:

    @Override 
    public void init() throws ServletException
    {
        super.init();
        System.clearProperty(&quot;javax.net.ssl.trustStore&quot;);
    }

If your JDK needs to work with this property, you need to set it in a different manner.
&lt;br&gt;Why? &lt;br&gt;
Run this code in a normal environment (without any containers, just compile and run.)
Then run it inside of your servlet, with your Web App(Instead of system println, You can print the result on a sample webpage.)

    System.out.println(System.getProperty(&quot;javax.net.ssl.trustStore&quot;));

You can see that with/without glassfish, results come out quite differently.
Result with glassfish:

    /Users/jianqing/GlassFish_Server/glassfish/domains/domain1/config/cacerts.jks

Result without glassfish:

    null

Everything works fine again when it&#39;s set to null.

